/modsCollection/mods/note	W.A. Wilkes was the expert accountant. Alberta inquiry opened in Medicine Hat on June 10, 1907, and sittings were also held in Lethbridge, Cardston, Macleod, High River, Calgary, Gleichen, Innisfail, Red Deer, Lacombe, Erskine, Wetaskiwin, Edmonton, Vegreville, and Vermilion, concluding July 22, 1907. Alberta edition of the report not located. The only edition located is the one tabled in the Manitoba Legislative Assembly as its Sessional Paper 5 of 1908.	http://royal.library.ualberta.ca/royalcommissions/dspCitation.cfm?ID=13	book	1	3-6

/modsCollection/mods/note	Alberta Royal Commission on the Alberta Great Waterways Railway Company Report. Not dated. Signed by N.D. Beck Chairman. Tabled in the Legislative Assembly November 10, 1910. Printed with no title page, as Commission [. . .] to enquire "Whether any, and if any, which officer, or officers of the Government or member or members of the Legislature of the Province were or are interested, either directly or indirectly, by themselves or through others, in the erection, incorporation, or organization of the Alberta and Great Waterways Railway Company [. . .]" By his signing the report, it is taken that N.D. Beck is the Chairman. Inquiry opened in Edmonton March 29, 1910, resumed April 14 in Edmonton, and continued later in Winnipeg and Toronto and Edmonton again. Evidence extends to 3,225 pages with 255 exhibits.	http://royal.library.ualberta.ca/royalcommissions/dspCitation.cfm?ID=17	book	1	3-6

/modsCollection/mods/note	Alberta's Oil Industry: The Report of a Royal Commission Appointed by the Government of the Province of Alberta Under the Public Inquiries Act to Inquiry into Matters Connected with Petroleum and Petroleum Products. Appointed on October 8, 1938 by Order in Council 1271/38 under the Public Inquiries Act (R.S.A. 1922, c.5) on the recommendation of the Minister of Trade and Industry and of a Resolution of the Legislative Assembly passed on March 24, 1938. Commission dated October 12, 1938 and reprinted in The Alberta Gazette of October 31, 1938, pp. 1059-1061. Questions regarding the cost of the Commission answered in the Journals of the Legislative Assembly February 13, 1940. 747 exhibits were presented and 15,674 pages of verbal testimony taken. Arguments were completed December 30, 1939.	http://royal.library.ualberta.ca/royalcommissions/dspCitation.cfm?ID=42	book	1	3-6

/modsCollection/mods/note	Appointed on December 31, 1957 by Order Council 2009/57 under the Public Inquiries Act (R.S.A. 1955, c. 258) on the recommendation of the Minister of Education. Commission dated December 31, 1957 and reprinted in the Alberta Gazette of January 15, 1958, pp. 1-4. Letter of transmittal dated November 9, 1959. Tabled in the Legislative Assembly February 15, 1960. Printed as Report of the Royal Commission on Education in Alberta. Research Director: Russell S. MacArthur. Sessions were held for more than two hundred days over twenty-two months. 191 briefs were submitted. The cost of the Commission is outlined in Sessional Paper 1960-76. For appointment of Commission staff, see Order in Council 117/58. For a list of and abstracts of the studies completed for the Commission, see the report. Report includes minority report of John S. /modsCollection/mods/note	Tabled in the Legislative Assembly March 23, 1948. Andrew Stewart acted as consultant and advisor. Eric John Hanson was engaged to assist the Commission by Order in Council 919/47. For Commission expenses, see Orders in Council 794/47, 1048/47 and 1304/47. Sixty-two briefs were submitted. Public hearings were held in Medicine Hat, Lethbridge, Calgary, Edmonton, Drumheller, Red Deer, Vermilion, Peace River and Grande Prairie. The Throne Speech of February 20, 1947 announced the government's intention to hold this inquiry.	http://royal.library.ualberta.ca/royalcommissions/dspCitation.cfm?ID=50	book	1	3-6

/modsCollection/mods/note	Printed as: In the Matter of: The Public Inquiries Act, being Chapter 296, R.S.A. 1970 and Amendments there to; and In the Matter of: a Royal Commission dated the 21st day of February, 1974 directed to the Honourable Mr. Justice Cairns to inquire into the affairs of the Alberta Housing Corporation as set out particularly in the Commission Report. Hearings were held in Edmonton for 24 days beginning on May 6 and concluding November 21, 1974. 83 exhibits were filed and 50 witnesses heard. The evidence comprises 24 volumes. /modsCollection/mods/note	Appointed on February 22, 1973 by Order in Council 290/73 under Section 2 of the Public Inquiries Act (R.S.A. 1970, c. 296) on the recommendation of the minister of Municipal Affairs. Commission dated March 14, 1973 and reprinted in the report. Letter of transmittal dated November 30, 1973. Liaison and Clerk of the Hearings: J.C. Richl. Hearings were held in Grande Cache beginning May 29, 1973, and in Edmonton June 11, 1973. 1800 pages of testimony were taken and 64 witnesses heard. Report includes minority report of Commissioner Patching. Ministerial announcements were made in the Legislative Assembly of the appointment of the Commission on February 22, 1973 and of the two additional members on March 9, 1973.
